<TITLE> Farming to go 'high-tech': PM </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 19 (bdnews24.com) - Prime minister Sheikh Hasina said the government would go high-tech to ensure food security and boost output, her press secretary informed reporters Thursday. "The government plans to apply latest technology to make qualitative changes for ensuring a modern agriculture sector," Abul Kalam Azad quoted Hasina as telling UN Food and Agriculture Organisation representative Ad Spijkers. Spijkers met the prime minister at the latter's office Thursday. Hasina briefed the UN official on her government's plans to increase the number of godowns and silos for preservation of grains. The two discussed ways to turn Bangladesh into a "food surplus" country, Azad said. Hasina said forestation programmes would be undertaken to decrease salinity in the southern regions and increase navigability of the rivers. Private sectors will be encouraged to invest, the premier said. The government will also encourage farmers to grow more organic products, she said. Discussing the global recession, Hasina informed Spijkers of the just-formed task force to counter its impact, which would sit from Mar 24. The prime minister's press secretary said Spijkers praised the previous Awami League government's steps to attain surplus food supply in the country. Hasina thanked FAO for its assistance in the aftermath of 2007's Cyclone Sidr
